2024–2025 Handbook: Western High Chorus & Vocal Music Programs

Creating lifelong musicians since 1981

The Handbook is a guide for students and parents involved in the Western High School Chorus & Vocal Music programs. Western Chorus has been performing since WHS opened in 1981.

In Chorus, you are responsible for our reputation, by assuming the role of professional student-musician. You’re responsible to achieve an expert understanding of music, musicianship, and what it means to be an artist. Use your time effectively, and your participation in Chorus will be fun and enjoyable for you and for your fellow singers.

What do we do here? Western Chorus has earned ratings of “Superior” and “Superior with Distinction”, at state-level evaluations. The exclusive Western Singers have toured throughout Florida and the South. Select ensembles have been chosen to perform at Carnegie Hall, and other venues, in New York City. Our singers traveled to New York City to perform as guests of the renowned Festival Singers of Florida. The Western Legatos a cappella group opened for the Yale Spizzwinks, the oldest college a cappella ensemble in the nation, in addition to performing for Broward’s U.S. Congress delegation. Western’s Concert Chorus performed at Carnegie Hall multiple times as part of the National Concert Chorus. You may already know that Western Chorus has performed regularly at the Walt Disney World Candlelight Processional, for over twenty–five years. Among our thousands of alumni are singers, Grammy® nominees and winners, music producers, choir directors, and lifelong musicians.

Welcome to our world of musical art, where we shall strive to create beautiful and unique sounds with each other, for our listeners. I can’t wait to step into this “universe of possibilities” with you.

Brandon R Monse, MME
Choral Music Director & Fine Arts Dept. Chair
Western High School

Student/Family Checklist

  • Read the Handbook completely, to avoid surprises

  • Return Participation Contract, Annual Field Trip Form, Permission Form for Medical Treatment, Afterschool Supplemental Programs Form

  • Install Remind on your phone immediately and join your classes. 2nd pd. @singerswhs, 4th pd. @choruswhs.

  • Take the Handbook Quiz on Canvas, when directed in class. Everyone must earn 80% on the Handbook Quiz to pass it. If you get less than 80%, retake.

  • Visit westernchorus.com. Locate the Calendar and subscribe to it on your device’s calendar app.

  • Follow @westernchorus on social media.

  • Keep the Handbook in a convenient spot for reference.

  • Read and sign Honors Contract (if you are enrolled in an Honors class)

Certain officers are Student Conductors. In this role, they lead other singers on the conductor’s podium. Singers are required to treat any conductor with the same respect as the Director; inappropriate behavior during student-led time is poor musicianship and will result in intervention.

Everyday Things

  • participate in all activities, rehearsals, and performances; including correct posture; and with all required materials

  • maintain your folder, student-supplied 1” black matte binder (no clear plastic covers please), and uniforms

  • contribute to the ensemble

  • cooperate with other class members, officers, and director

Objectives for All Singers

  1. to be able to perform alone and in a group.

  2. to be able to create artistic music

  3. to be able to use the vocabulary and notation of music.

  4. to be able to perform properly with their voice, and be cognizant of its care.

  5. to be able to respond to music aesthetically, intellectually, and emotionally.

  6. to be able to continue their musical involvement individually.

  7. to become acquainted with a wide variety of musical styles and uses.

  8. to develop a feeling of support for community music activities.

  9. to develop individual leadership and teamwork characteristics.

Mr. Monse’s ❺ rules

① Be prompt

be on time and ready to start at the bell

② Be prepared

have your music, pencil, and required equipment ready. Phones must be parked where indicated.

③ Be respectful

to all people, facilities, furniture, music

④ Be engaged

all singers must be actively participating in all activities, be on task, phones parked (FL law and district policy)

❺ Be a leader

you do not have to be an “officer” to lead — lead from any chair.

1. What Fun Things Can I Do in Chorus?

Walt Disney World Candlelight Processional

Tentative: Nov/Dec 2024
(singers are expected to perform if the Chorus is accepted and they are assigned)

Holiday season show at EPCOT, the Candlelight Processional includes a massed choir, 50-piece live orchestra, and a celebrity narrator. An American Sign Language interpreter is also on stage. The Chorus generally applies for this event each year based on availability. Limited to ~50 students. Western prioritizes students by Chorus seniority, audition, and director discretion.

Florida All-State Choruses

presented by Florida Music Education Association & Florida Vocal Association
Tampa, January 2025

A great opportunity for highly-motivated, talented singers! Auditioned groups of the best high school musicians in Florida. In order to audition, students first need to pass a written musicianship exam and a sight reading test, then learn the selected All-State songs. The singer must pass a vocal audition. Those with the highest scores throughout Florida will be eligible to sing in one of several choruses which will assemble in Tampa in January for the annual Florida Music Education Conference. To be chosen a member of an All-State Chorus is one of the highest honors and one of the greatest experiences any high school singer can achieve. After-school practices will be held throughout August and September. (~$20 registration fee for audition, appreciable additional expenses if accepted to attend All-State in Tampa). Participation requires director approval and attendance at practice sessions.

All-County Honor Chorus

Broward Music Education Association
Coral Springs, Jan–Feb 2025

The Broward All-County Honor Chorus is another opportunity for talented singers! Upon nomination, students may sign up, learn the assigned music, and perform for honors. Singers must attend all scheduled rehearsals and concerts. Rehearsals are held at Coral Glades High School. Concert held at one of the fine performing arts centers in the area. In the event of high interest, the director will select eligible students. (Participation fee applies. Requires approval.)

American Choral Directors Association National Honor Choirs

at ACDA National Conference
Dallas, Texas, Mar 2025

These highly-select choirs are formed of the best auditioned singers in the whole country, in alternating years. Singers are required to attend all scheduled rehearsals and concerts as well as stay in pre-designated hotels at the regional and/or national conference of ACDA. To be selected for an Honor Choir is a grand honor and one of the most memorable and greatest experiences any singer can achieve. Students are financially liable for their own participation, must provide a parent chaperone, and are permitted to audition only at the discretion of the Director. (Fees apply. Requires approval.)

National Concert Chorus

New York City, New York
Tentative: Apr, May, or June 2025

Massed choir including Western’s singers performs at the world-famous Carnegie Hall or other reputable venue in Manhattan, NYC. Tentative trip always includes roundtrip air transportation, rehearsal and performance venue with distinguished conductors, hotel, sightseeing and shows. WHS NYC tours occur approximately every 3–5 years when possible. Participation requires director approval, attendance at practice sessions, and may involve significant costs which may be defrayed by fundraising.

Student Officers

You may apply to be a chorus officer for the 2025–26 school year. Applications will open during the final quarter. Officers meet every two weeks after school for 30–45 minutes, or virtually. All students: In order to pass the handbook test you will need this answer: Broward Leon Orange Palm Beach. If at any time an officer does not perform his/her duties, the Executive Board has the right to petition for a new appointment. This may be done only when 51% of Executive Board members agree in writing and present their petition with signatures to the director. All Officers serve at the pleasure of the Director.

All officers must be in attendance at all Chorus activities, including extra- and co-curricular events.

2. Important Stuff

2.1. Web Site, e-mail, Social Media, Texts

The official Chorus website is www.westernchorus.com. You can follow @westernchorus on Instagram, “X” aka Twitter, YouTube, Facebook, SoundCloud.

Use the Remind app to subscribe to announcements for your class — do this now. These announcements will be in addition to Canvas and Focus Announcements and you are required to receive them. This is a free service. You must resubscribe each year.

  • Period 2: @singerswhs

  • Period 4: @choruswhs

2.2. Music Technology Experience Center

In addition to Canvas, MTEC Cloud hosts one of the online components of the choral curriculum. Students are required to print forms, complete assignments and vocal practice, and create online audio recordings on MTEC and Canvas. A modern browser is required. Some assignments will require visiting the Music Technology Experience Center (Rm. 428), to be completed on specialized music apps.

2.3. Official Calendar

The official Calendar is located on the Chorus Website and supersedes ANY other calendar information. Grading is partially based on participation at events listed in this official Calendar, so please check it often. Events on the Calendar will change as performances are scheduled. Chorus students/parents are responsible to schedule appointments to not miss rehearsals & performances. The Calendar will always be the master location of chorus events. Subscribe to Calendar push notifications via Google Calendar / Apple Calendar on your phone so that you always…

“KNOW WHAT YOU ARE EXPECTED TO DO”

2.4. Retreat

The annual Chorus Retreat is held on a Friday at WHS. Students will participate in group bonding games and activities, rehearse, have open mic, and dinner will be served. Retreat is mandatory for all students in chorus, and is a graded +Rehearsal, no exceptions Date/time TBA.

2.5. Student Accounts & Obligations

“Accounts” are provided to members of the Chorus in order to facilitate the payment of trip fees, ensemble fees, etc. Certain fundraising activities distribute a portion of profits into accounts. Students who do not participate in fundraising cannot enjoy the benefits of this system. The Director reserves the right to debit student accounts for any money owed. Money collected in the name of the Chorus remains with the Chorus. Remaining fees and fundraising monies are property of the program and do not rollover from year to year.

Students will be held financially liable for any loss of department materials. Obligations will be issued for any liability.

2.6. Co-Curricular Music Activities — FSMA

“Some activities are co-curricular, meaning the activity is an extension of the classroom curriculum, as defined in lesson plans for a state approved academic course/elective. Band, orchestra, and chorus classes are “performance” classes in which the performance is an important portion of the assessment for the “unit” taught. (The performance is equivalent to a unit test.) Therefore, it is fully appropriate for students who are members of bands, orchestras, and choruses to study musical selections, rehearse them …​for a period of time, have individual assessments, and then a culminating performance as a part of the evaluation of the student, as well as the progress of the class.

As the Evaluation/Festivals, sanctioned by the FSMA, are the culminating activities in the state for marching band, concert band - orchestra - chorus, where students spend a number of weeks in preparation; as the Evaluation/Festivals are not competitions, but are evaluations of music organizations; and as the preparation for participation in the evaluation/festival does include and support curriculum as defined in the Curriculum Framework for the Arts, the performance at these specific events should be considered co-curricular.”

— Florida School Music Association

Florida course narrative:

This course requires students to participate in extra rehearsals and performances beyond the school day to support, extend, and assess learning in the classroom.

2.7. Use of Personal Electronics

On July 23, 2024, the School Board voted to limit access to wireless communication devices for students during instructional time, defined as the time from the first bell of the day until the end of the school day, including passing periods and lunchtime. It is important to distinguish that this is not a ban on cell phones or other technology; it is meant to elevate student learning and allow students to Disconnect to Reconnect in a distraction-free environment.

As part of musicianship grade, students are required to park their personal wireless communication devices in the assigned area (slot, charging station, etc.) for the entire period, rehearsal, or performance. This must be done upon room entry; DO NOT WAIT TO BE ASKED.

Reading and Marking Music on Tablets

Students may choose to use a personal 10" or larger tablet (NOT PHONE) and stylus for the reading and marking of sheet music scores (only), with scorereading apps which allow fast marking, page turns, and reference points. REQUIRED: ForScore (iPadOS, $19.99) or MobileSheetsPro (Android, $14.99); these apps are not free and any student choosing to use this method shall incur the cost. Off-task tablet or phone use may result in a 0% and device confiscation. School staff will not be responsible for loss or damage to personal electronics. Students may always elect to read their music the traditional way.

SCHOOL BOARD WIRELESS DEVICE POLICY WILL BE ENFORCED. TABLETS MAY ONLY BE USED IN ACCORDANCE WITH THE ABOVE GUIDELINES FOR MUSIC READING IN AIRPLANE MODE WITH WI-FI OFF. ALL OTHER USES ARE PROHIBITED DURING CLASS UNLESS OTHERWISE DIRECTED.

Unauthorized use of phones/devices in the rehearsal room will result in a zero (0%) class rehearsal grade for that day upon the first violation. There will be no verbal warnings.

Phones must remain out of sight at all times, including transitional times in class, rehearsals, etc. unless directed by school staff, including at co-curricular events.

Florida law prohibits student use of wireless communications devices during school instructional time unless directed by staff. Additionally, The Code Of Student Conduct (SBBC Policy #5.8) permits confiscation of phones by School Board staff, to be returned only to parent. SCHOOL BOARD STAFF WILL NOT BE HELD LIABLE FOR DEVICES THAT ARE LOST, STOLEN, OR CONFISCATED.

2.8. Concert Attire

Students are assigned to perform in different attire throughout the year. Students are required to supply specific items; others will be loaned. Students are financially liable for any school-owned property that is loaned to them. Failure to return in the required condition will result in financial obligations to the school.

Formal uniform: Assigned chorus dress, closed-toe black dress shoes with no heels. Assigned pearl set if directed. Men: Black long-sleeved dress shirt with black buttons, black dress pants, black socks, black shoes, black belt. Tie will be provided. No other jewelry.

T-Shirt uniform: Assigned chorus t-shirt (purchased by student with Fair Share). Dark blue jeans with no visible holes, tears, or distressing. Closed-toed shoes with socks.

Western Singers golf shirt uniform: Assigned Western Singers chorus golf shirt (purchased by Singers at the E-Store). Dark blue jeans with no visible holes, tears, or distressing. Closed-toed shoes with socks.

Other uniforms as determined.

WCBC, Inc. is a tax-exempt corporation of parents, guardians, and members of the community who desire to help Western Chorus raise funds and promote the program. Boosters meet throughout the year. Individuals interested in supporting the choral program as a Booster, or who have innovative fundraising ideas, should contact WCBC at the address below.

Stay tuned for information about upcoming Booster events!

2.10. Fair Share

All students shall convey their Fair Share by the given deadline, or will receive an obligation. Students will not be excluded from participation due to financial burden, but must make alternative arrangements with the director before Fair Share is due.

2.11. Facilities & Office

Gum, food, and drink are NEVER allowed in music facilities. The only exception is water in a spill-proof bottle. Bring water to rehearsal.

The Director’s Office is a private office, not part of the choral students' universe. Students should never be in the office without permission of the director. Additionally, students must never occupy any music practice rooms or use the MTEC Lab without music faculty authorization.

2.12. ATTENDANCE

A Little Story

Some students invariably ask “What is the big deal if I miss rehearsal? I am just one person…they can do without me.” Or, “I’ve never missed a rehearsal before.” Or this old classic: “I already know my music.” To those who would ask such questions, see below:

On Being a “Kxy Person”

Xvxn though my laptop is an old modxl, it works quitx wxll xxcxpt that thxrx is a problxm with onx kxy. Thxrx arx 119 othxr kxys that function wxll xnough, but just onx kxy not working makxs a big diffxrxncx. Somxtimxs, it sxxms to mx that a musical group is somxwhat likx my computxr: Not all thx kxys arx always working propxrly. You may say, “Wxll, I am only onx pxrson; it won’t makx much of a diffxrxncx if I don’t givx 100%.” But, you sxx, thx Chorus, to bx xffxctivx, nxxds thx activx participation of xvxry pxrson, xvxry day. So thx nxxt timx you think you arx only onx pxrson, and that your xffort is not nxxdxd, rxmxmbxr my laptop and rxalizx this:

You arx a kxy pxrson, and you arx nxxdxd vxry much. Wx can’t succxxd without you.

Everyone must attend concerts, rehearsals, and events. These occur during school, and occasionally during non-school hours — such as Retreat. Performing in any music ensemble requires team effort so skipping any event will be considered poor musicianship. Students may earn 20 class rehearsal points daily. Unexcused absences from daily class rehearsal: -20 points from Class Rehearsal grade; unexcused tardies: -15 points. Due to the “one-time” nature of choral rehearsals, any excusable tardy or absence will result in the withholding of 5 points from the weekly participation grade.

Summary: You must be in class and participating correctly, in order to earn class rehearsal points.

“Early is on time, on time is late,
late is unthinkable”

You are a kxy pxrson. Affect your chorus positively: be punctual and contribute.

All students must attend Main Concerts, as well as district and state Music Performance Assessments (MPAs). An Inexcusable absence from a Main Concert or MPA will result in course failure for that term. Students who miss concert(s) may not be allowed to attend trips.

District MPA, held at a local school, provides an opportunity for the Chorus to receive an outside, professional adjudication of our performance. For this reason, all students must participate in the District MPA, and, if their Chorus ensembles qualify and register, the State MPA.

Excusable absences from rehearsals and performances, including those outside school hours:

  • communicable illness on the student’s part (doctor’s note required, and please e-mail the Chorus Office to let us know why you will be missing rehearsal)

  • a death in the immediate family (documented)

  • a religious obligation (note from religious official required)

  • wedding/major family event

  • receiving a Pulitzer Prize for Music

  • receiving a Grammy

In cases of extreme illness, please contact the Chorus Office as soon as possible. A student seeking excusability for illness must present a doctor letter to the Chorus Office — no exceptions.

Students must be picked up promptly at the end of rehearsal and shouldn’t be waiting in front of the school. Parents, please don’t wait for a phone call or text, before coming to school to pick up a student. If any student is waiting 15 minutes after an event concludes, Davie Police Department will have to be called to pick up the abandoned student. Along the same lines, class and other events will be dismissed by DIRECTOR ONLY. Students will not be dismissed early because “SOMEONE IS WAITING OUTSIDE.” This is a serious safety concern and will be enforced. Students leaving before being dismissed by the Director earn 0% for that activity. This is effectively wandering off, and students may not wander off from scheduled events.

Inexcusable absences from rehearsals & performances, including those outside school hours, comprise, for example: work, transportation problems, babysitting for family or others, doctor or dental appointment, sports practice, detentions, homework/studying for a test, club meetings, driving exam, family trip/vacation, unexcused absence from school. Inexcusable absences from performances will result in letter-grade deductions or failure and the possibility that students will not be allowed to participate in any or all future choral events. Understand that unlike club meetings and sports…​

Chorus events are academic assignments. They are not extracurricular activities.

…​and you will be graded on your participation and musicianship. You may not miss or be tardy to Chorus events for extracurricular club meetings; if you have a conflict, tell the Director so accommodations can be made. Concordantly, you may not withdraw from Chorus due to participation in sports or clubs. We will work with you so that you can balance your commitments.

Students: post your Chorus schedule at work so that they do not schedule you; employers are not allowed to interfere with schoolwork. The director will contact your job supervisor to discuss this, upon request.

Since Chorus events often take place after school, conflicts such as doctor appointments, which would be excused* during the school day, are not excusable when they result in missing an after-school choral event. Arrange your appointments around Chorus events. If you accidentally schedule a conflicting appointment, re-schedule it.

Everyone will appreciate it.

* Remember, there are no absences where you are “excused” from completing make-up work and would get points for doing no work. If you miss an event and believe your absence is excusable in accordance with this page, see the Director for make-up work and complete it within the allotted timeframe, to earn your points.

2.13. GRADING

① +Performances/+Rehearsal (on- or off-campus, during and/or after school, on task) & Tests

weight 0.41

② Class Rehearsal (daily & weekly rubric) including musicianship, punctuality, proper supplies, water, folder, singer’s Posture Levels, following Director & officer instructions, being on task, etc.

weight 0.34

③ Quizzes, Sight-Reading, Music Theory Class/Homework (written & other), Music Knowledge Evaluations, Sectional Rehearsals Musicianship

weight 0.25

U.S. federal law reinforces the role of music as a core subject in the well-rounded education of students. WHS Performing & Fine Arts Department Faculty hold our subject matter to the same standard to which all other core subjects are held.

If you are absent, provided the absence is excusable, you will have earned 0 points; you must make up the work or time missed in order to earn points.

If “Suzy Singer” was sick, and absent from school on the day of an English test, the English teacher would not simply give her 100% upon her return, even if her absence was “excused.” Suzy would still have to make up the test… The same concept applies to Chorus events. It is your responsibility to seek make up work for excusable absences.

Make-up assignments are selected at Director’s discretion.

2.14. Schedule Changes

Chorus classes are elective; students are not placed in a Chorus if they have not elected to take the course. Therefore, schedule changes are not authorized.

2.15. Security / ID Cards

Never prop open any doors in the music suite. Your student ID card must be worn around your neck and visible at all times on the WHS campus; including after school. ID Barcodes will be scanned for event attendance, uniform checkout, etc. Not wearing ID is poor musicianship.

2.16. Private Lessons

One-to-one lessons are vital to success for a young musician. Students who study privately with a professional show rapid improvement in individual musicianship. As that student improves, their contribution to their Chorus becomes stronger and greater. The director can assist you in locating a private voice teacher.

2.17. Travel

Chorus may take local and overnight trips, provided student participation is sufficient for a successful performance. Trip dates will be announced in advance, and monies paid will become nonrefundable after a specified date. When on trips, all program, school, and district rules apply. Students who do not obey rules or exhibit unacceptable attitude or behavior will be sent home at parents’ expense; such behaviors result in disciplinary actions upon return. Always try to fulfill the Chorus Vision:

Vision

In singing, we unite to form something bigger than any one of us. We are one voice, one heartbeat, one soul. Music is not just notes on a staff, but rather a connective resonance flowing through all of us, and it is our privilege to have the opportunity to convey art to the world.
— the students officers of Western Chorus class of 2013 
Have a great year in Chorus. We're so glad you are here!
